00:03:34.340 --> 00:03:36.380
So I started with the
premise that I wanted

00:03:36.380 --> 00:03:39.160
to make a science fiction.

00:03:39.160 --> 00:03:41.650
And my reason for being
interested in science fiction

00:03:41.650 --> 00:03:46.180
is I wanted to work between
fantasy and politics.

00:03:46.180 --> 00:03:49.270
I also am interested in
both utopia and dystopia.

00:03:49.270 --> 00:03:54.190
So for me, utopia is,
what's possible is

00:03:54.190 --> 00:03:55.810
what you can imagine.

00:03:55.810 --> 00:03:57.520
And dystopia is,
what's happening

00:03:57.520 --> 00:03:59.140
is worse than you can imagine.

00:04:03.070 --> 00:04:06.610
So I'm kind of flux between
those two worlds in this work.

00:04:06.610 --> 00:04:09.230
That means that there
are times when--

00:04:09.230 --> 00:04:12.070
well, let me just say that I
think that utopia is important,

00:04:12.070 --> 00:04:16.390
in terms of I believe all
political change stems

00:04:16.390 --> 00:04:20.620
from utopic visions.

00:04:20.620 --> 00:04:23.110
You have to think much bigger
than what you can accomplish.

00:04:23.110 --> 00:04:27.180
And that's the beginning step
to like moving progressively

00:04:27.180 --> 00:04:30.480
in kind of any
break with what we

00:04:30.480 --> 00:04:33.840
know is the sort of form
of politics or society

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:35.616
at any point.

00:04:35.616 --> 00:04:36.990
And for me, the
dystopic is a way

00:04:36.990 --> 00:04:40.290
to reflect on all
of the crap that's

00:04:40.290 --> 00:04:45.670
going on at the same time
that I'm making this work.

00:04:45.670 --> 00:04:48.210
Speculative present--
so this work

00:04:48.210 --> 00:04:52.170
is set in what I call
a speculative present.

00:04:52.170 --> 00:04:55.470
That means that I'm really
interested in the now.

00:04:55.470 --> 00:04:58.500
I'm interested in
the idea that the now

00:04:58.500 --> 00:05:05.650
is always becoming both the past
and the future simultaneously.

00:05:05.650 --> 00:05:08.962
So it's a highly active space.

00:05:08.962 --> 00:05:10.920
Also, I think if you want
to change the future,

00:05:10.920 --> 00:05:13.620
you have to change the now.

00:05:13.620 --> 00:05:18.980
So aesthetically, the way this
is set up is it doesn't have--

00:05:18.980 --> 00:05:20.730
it's a science
fiction that doesn't--

00:05:20.730 --> 00:05:23.730
it's not a 2001 Odyssey.

00:05:23.730 --> 00:05:30.180
We don't have slick, futuristic
machines, and spaceships,

00:05:30.180 --> 00:05:31.620
and things like that.

00:05:31.620 --> 00:05:35.340
I'm interested in like
that the future is--

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:38.190
I like to think of the
future like a iPhone

00:05:38.190 --> 00:05:40.830
with a cracked face.

00:05:40.830 --> 00:05:42.660
You have technology,
but you don't

00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:44.700
have enough money to fix it.

00:05:44.700 --> 00:05:46.578
OK?

00:05:46.578 --> 00:05:48.470
It seems a lot more practical.

00:05:48.470 --> 00:05:53.900
All right, acting agents, this
is another principle for me,

00:05:53.900 --> 00:05:55.970
is that the performers
in this work

00:05:55.970 --> 00:06:02.420
are not performing subjects,
or characters, or nouns even.

00:06:02.420 --> 00:06:05.390
They might be nouns,
actually, sometimes.

00:06:05.390 --> 00:06:08.640
But the performer's
actually actions.

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:09.800
They're phenomena.

00:06:09.800 --> 00:06:11.030
They're agents of change.

00:06:18.480 --> 00:06:24.030
They're symbolizing various
sort of metaphysical aspects

00:06:24.030 --> 00:06:25.009
of the world.

00:06:25.009 --> 00:06:26.550
And I'll explain
them more when I get

00:06:26.550 --> 00:06:28.475
to the different acting agents.

00:06:28.475 --> 00:06:30.600
But that also means that
I don't see the performers

00:06:30.600 --> 00:06:31.900
as protagonists.

00:06:31.900 --> 00:06:34.360
So it's an inversion of
thinking, cinematic thinking.

00:06:34.360 --> 00:06:39.510
I actually see the
site, or the stage,

00:06:39.510 --> 00:06:43.110
or whatever location I'm
working in as the protagonist.

00:06:43.110 --> 00:06:46.950
So in the first film, that's
the desert, or the black box

00:06:46.950 --> 00:06:47.460
theater.

00:06:47.460 --> 00:06:49.680
In the second one, it's
this building in which

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:51.390
the whole piece is set.

00:06:51.390 --> 00:06:54.030
And the last thing I want
to talk about to preface

00:06:54.030 --> 00:06:58.080
this is, matter is what does.

00:06:58.080 --> 00:07:05.910
So that is, a thinking in
which all matter is animate.

00:07:05.910 --> 00:07:10.050
It's an idea of acknowledging
that all matter is constantly

00:07:10.050 --> 00:07:11.170
changing.

00:07:11.170 --> 00:07:16.080
There's nothing
consistent about matter.

00:07:16.080 --> 00:07:21.390
And so if we start to look kind
of fundamentally at the tiniest

00:07:21.390 --> 00:07:30.640
parts of our being as
constantly changing,

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:33.610
the things that we see as
fixed are really just ways

00:07:33.610 --> 00:07:35.050
that we organize the world.

00:07:35.050 --> 00:07:39.370
And so this is a little
bit about entering

00:07:39.370 --> 00:07:43.660
an alternate space of accepting
that the order of things

00:07:43.660 --> 00:07:48.640
is not as we perceive
them inherently.

00:07:48.640 --> 00:07:49.940
Oh, and queer--

00:07:49.940 --> 00:07:53.170
OK, one more.

00:07:53.170 --> 00:07:56.170
So queer, for me, is
something that I would

00:07:56.170 --> 00:08:01.329
like to sort of divorce from.

00:08:01.329 --> 00:08:03.120
I don't want to divorce
it from its history

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:09.220
as a word from the homosexual
movement and narrative.

00:08:09.220 --> 00:08:11.470
I think it's important that
it hold onto that history.

00:08:11.470 --> 00:08:15.640
But I think it's
not really useful.

00:08:15.640 --> 00:08:19.840
That's not a useful
anchor in its meaning now

00:08:19.840 --> 00:08:22.230
or in the future.

00:08:22.230 --> 00:08:26.380
And by that, I mean I
have friends who are--

00:08:26.380 --> 00:08:30.580
a trans woman and
a trans man dating.

00:08:30.580 --> 00:08:33.630
Are they homosexuals?

00:08:33.630 --> 00:08:36.667
No, but they're queer.

00:08:36.667 --> 00:08:38.500
There's a lot of other
examples I could use.

00:08:38.500 --> 00:08:40.679
But I think that
what I want to think

00:08:40.679 --> 00:08:45.630
about queer as is a
space of what I'm calling

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:47.220
un-assimilated difference.

00:08:47.220 --> 00:08:49.200
And then it also
becomes, maybe, a space

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:51.720
for a more kind of
intersectional thinking

00:08:51.720 --> 00:08:54.780
about what a queer body
is, and that it's not

00:08:54.780 --> 00:08:57.330
fixed to your sexual
orientation inherently.

00:08:57.330 --> 00:09:00.000
And there's a lot of
un-assimilated bodies

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:01.790
in the world--

00:09:01.790 --> 00:09:03.900
and that we might
advocate for that,

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:07.050
or champion that as a
better way of moving

00:09:07.050 --> 00:09:11.730
through the world instead
of assimilation, which

00:09:11.730 --> 00:09:13.080
is how most things work.

00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:17.310
OK, "A Smeary Spot," here we go.

00:09:17.310 --> 00:09:24.162
So the installation
is a four-channel.

00:09:24.162 --> 00:09:25.620
There's three large
channels, which

00:09:25.620 --> 00:09:30.330
are like 7 foot screens,
7 by 12 foot screens.

00:09:30.330 --> 00:09:34.740
And then there's a small monitor
at the end, which you can see.

00:09:34.740 --> 00:09:36.960
And that cycles
through the credits.

00:09:36.960 --> 00:09:39.750
The credits are kept
separate, so that the film

00:09:39.750 --> 00:09:42.810
can run as a seamless loop.

00:09:42.810 --> 00:09:51.632
And also because the credits
are not just everyone

00:09:51.632 --> 00:09:52.590
who worked on the film.

00:09:52.590 --> 00:09:54.390
But they also carry
some like kind

00:09:54.390 --> 00:09:57.330
of footnotes that maybe give
you some of the information

00:09:57.330 --> 00:09:58.530
that I was just giving.

00:09:58.530 --> 00:10:00.220
It's different than the
information I just gave you,

00:10:00.220 --> 00:10:01.890
but there's a lot
of clues about how

00:10:01.890 --> 00:10:06.730
to read the work that is in the
way that I wrote the credits.

00:10:06.730 --> 00:10:11.220
So I'm treating the credits
kind of as their own piece.

00:10:11.220 --> 00:10:11.989
This is similar.

00:10:11.989 --> 00:10:13.530
I just brightened
this one up, so you

00:10:13.530 --> 00:10:15.550
can see it a little better.

00:10:15.550 --> 00:10:19.980
But also, the three
screams are installed

00:10:19.980 --> 00:10:25.830
at like a 10 degree angle in the
space, so that they actually--

00:10:25.830 --> 00:10:28.440
this is a very long space
that was installed in,

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:30.600
sort of narrow corridor.

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:36.620
That angle in the wall
makes the work kind

00:10:36.620 --> 00:10:39.830
of hold the space
in a way that's

00:10:39.830 --> 00:10:43.696
very different than when
projections happen on a wall

00:10:43.696 --> 00:10:44.570
or on a flat surface.

00:10:44.570 --> 00:10:48.141
They become sort of bodies
or presences of their own.

00:10:48.141 --> 00:10:49.640
And I'm really
interested in the way

00:10:49.640 --> 00:10:53.270
video is and can be sculptural.

00:10:53.270 --> 00:10:58.370
Also, the seating
is an office chairs.

00:10:58.370 --> 00:11:00.710
Part of that is there's
office chairs that

00:11:00.710 --> 00:11:02.130
show up in the video.

00:11:02.130 --> 00:11:04.310
But also, I'm interested
in this like--

00:11:04.310 --> 00:11:06.200
they kind of imply
labor, but labor that

00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:08.450
happens while you're seated.

00:11:08.450 --> 00:11:12.002
And I want you to be
a very active viewer.

00:11:12.002 --> 00:11:13.460
There's also six
channels of sound.

00:11:13.460 --> 00:11:18.467
And the sound moves from screen
to screen, or brackets you.

00:11:18.467 --> 00:11:19.175
It's very active.

00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:28.110
I actually hope that someone is
motivated to move with the work

00:11:28.110 --> 00:11:31.235
to a certain degree, even if
it's just their attention.

00:11:34.090 --> 00:11:36.990
In this installation,
there's also--

00:11:36.990 --> 00:11:37.990
I've installed it twice.

00:11:37.990 --> 00:11:40.156
And there's been two different
sculptures like this.

00:11:40.156 --> 00:11:41.050
And so this is one.

00:11:41.050 --> 00:11:43.300
It's a process that I've
been using for a while, where

00:11:43.300 --> 00:11:44.740
I've been casting sand.

00:11:44.740 --> 00:11:47.429
So that's sand that
I dyed that's black.

00:11:47.429 --> 00:11:48.970
Those are the
sandbags, that are also

00:11:48.970 --> 00:11:51.400
cast into it-- the white bits.

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:55.120
And then the top
chunk is concrete.

00:11:55.120 --> 00:11:57.520
So it's got this
kind of strange kind

00:11:57.520 --> 00:12:02.260
of strata sort of cavernous
natural form meeting

00:12:02.260 --> 00:12:11.140
this industrial sort
of building bit--

00:12:11.140 --> 00:12:14.890
industrial building bit, yes.

00:12:14.890 --> 00:12:19.710
And ensconced in that is what--
may be hard to see-- but it

00:12:19.710 --> 00:12:23.200
you can see kind of the
spine of the office chair.

00:12:23.200 --> 00:12:28.330
So I was sort of interested in--

00:12:28.330 --> 00:12:32.110
the chair is this object
of mobility, or movement,

00:12:32.110 --> 00:12:34.900
or fluidity in
the room, and then

00:12:34.900 --> 00:12:44.720
this kind of fossilizing of that
object in this sort of Earth

00:12:44.720 --> 00:12:46.599
monument piece.

00:12:46.599 --> 00:12:48.140
And those are the
wheels sticking out

00:12:48.140 --> 00:12:49.700
of the top of the work.

00:12:49.700 --> 00:12:51.980
This is another
version of this, which

00:12:51.980 --> 00:12:54.590
is the chair has been taken
apart a little bit more.

00:12:54.590 --> 00:12:57.050
And it's displayed
on pedestals that

00:12:57.050 --> 00:13:00.200
are made out of
the packing boxes

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:03.760
that the chairs were shipped in.

00:13:03.760 --> 00:13:07.030
And then the work is
actually cast inside the box.

00:13:07.030 --> 00:13:10.870
So the shape of the work is--

00:13:10.870 --> 00:13:15.310
you can see some of the relief,
I think, of the cardboard

00:13:15.310 --> 00:13:18.215
in the sand casting.

00:13:18.215 --> 00:13:20.590
All right, the other thing
that's on display in this work

00:13:20.590 --> 00:13:25.470
is this poster, which is
the script for the work.

00:13:25.470 --> 00:13:31.590
And part of the reason I gave
the script is because what I've

00:13:31.590 --> 00:13:35.730
done is collected a
lot of texts that I

00:13:35.730 --> 00:13:39.450
was reading that influenced
the making of this work.

00:13:39.450 --> 00:13:42.810
And I wove the text together.

00:13:42.810 --> 00:13:45.750
But also, they're being
recited in the work

00:13:45.750 --> 00:13:47.850
by different acting agents.

00:13:52.830 --> 00:13:55.030
One thing I had an issue
with is some of the texts

00:13:55.030 --> 00:13:58.350
were coming from
like theory texts.

00:13:58.350 --> 00:14:05.380
And so they're terribly dull
to listen to someone recite.

00:14:05.380 --> 00:14:08.590
So I took some liberties to
change some of the language

00:14:08.590 --> 00:14:12.880
to make it, let's say,
readable, reciteable,

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:14.560
without changing the
meaning too much.

00:14:14.560 --> 00:14:15.610
And then the other
thing that was

00:14:15.610 --> 00:14:18.070
important to me, is a lot of
theory texts and other texts,

00:14:18.070 --> 00:14:22.900
when they refer to humans, they
usually use the word he, right?

00:14:22.900 --> 00:14:24.670
So it's often gendered.

00:14:24.670 --> 00:14:26.560
So in any place where
gender shows up,

00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:29.560
I've gone in and
made it first person.

00:14:29.560 --> 00:14:34.210
So you can see it says, like, "I
became" in that line up there.

00:14:34.210 --> 00:14:36.790
But it was important to me, that
if I'm taking other people's

00:14:36.790 --> 00:14:38.581
words, and especially
if I'm altering them,

00:14:38.581 --> 00:14:43.260
that it was revealed in some
way in the installation.

00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:47.140
This work is set
in two locations.

00:14:47.140 --> 00:14:52.510
One part of it takes place
in a black box theater.

00:14:52.510 --> 00:14:57.670
The theater is something I came
to after being in the desert.

00:14:57.670 --> 00:14:59.830
And I was thinking a
lot about the desert

00:14:59.830 --> 00:15:05.020
as a kind of negative
space, thinking a lot

00:15:05.020 --> 00:15:07.270
about the fullness
of that absence

00:15:07.270 --> 00:15:09.210
that you feel when you're
in a space that big.

00:15:09.210 --> 00:15:15.092
Also, and a lot of ideas about
the chapter that I will develop

00:15:15.092 --> 00:15:17.050
about the void started
to come into play, where

00:15:17.050 --> 00:15:21.180
I was thinking, in
this site of absences

00:15:21.180 --> 00:15:23.350
is, again, like sort
of the most potential.

00:15:23.350 --> 00:15:25.840
And the theater became a
really good analogy for that.

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:29.410
Because one, on film,
the black box theater

00:15:29.410 --> 00:15:31.635
dissipates into sort of nothing.

00:15:31.635 --> 00:15:33.010
Because you can
give the illusion

00:15:33.010 --> 00:15:37.300
of emerging from nothing.

00:15:37.300 --> 00:15:40.300
And also that the theater is
a space of constant becoming.

00:15:40.300 --> 00:15:42.130
It's always making
and unmaking itself.

00:15:44.840 --> 00:15:51.880
And the other thing that's
central in the theater space

00:15:51.880 --> 00:15:53.750
is this waste pile.

00:15:53.750 --> 00:15:57.100
So this waste pile was inspired
by a quote by Jack Smith.

00:15:57.100 --> 00:16:00.710
Jack Smith was a filmmaker
and performance artist

00:16:00.710 --> 00:16:06.010
prominent in the '50s and '60s,
a queer icon of sorts, for me,

00:16:06.010 --> 00:16:06.700
certainly.

00:16:09.220 --> 00:16:11.740
So he imagined a
society where the dump

00:16:11.740 --> 00:16:15.400
is the central site of economic
and intellectual exchange.

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:18.100
So this is really a
homage to that idea.

00:16:18.100 --> 00:16:21.190
And everything that happens
in the theater is built from

00:16:21.190 --> 00:16:23.440
or goes back into this pile.

00:16:28.470 --> 00:16:30.310
And then the desert--

00:16:30.310 --> 00:16:32.920
so I can't give you
the whole background

00:16:32.920 --> 00:16:35.410
story of getting to the desert.

00:16:35.410 --> 00:16:40.520
But let's just say, I fell
in love with the Utah desert.

00:16:40.520 --> 00:16:42.800
And while I was there,
one of the big things

00:16:42.800 --> 00:16:45.560
that emerged for me
was I found myself

00:16:45.560 --> 00:16:47.820
on a lot of public lands.

00:16:47.820 --> 00:16:52.175
And this also became a
kind of foundational thing

00:16:52.175 --> 00:16:54.050
for how I was going to
think about this work.

00:17:00.410 --> 00:17:02.960
I guess maybe I should
give a little background

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:04.609
on public lands.

00:17:04.609 --> 00:17:06.190
People know what
public lands are?

00:17:06.190 --> 00:17:07.790
Yes, no?

00:17:07.790 --> 00:17:09.109
Yes.

00:17:09.109 --> 00:17:10.557
Do we have time for that?

00:17:10.557 --> 00:17:12.890
How about this, research
public lands if you don't know.

00:17:12.890 --> 00:17:15.348
I probably don't have enough
time to tell you all about it.

00:17:15.348 --> 00:17:16.640
I'm so sorry.

00:17:16.640 --> 00:17:18.740
Anyway, so public
lands, in a brief,

00:17:18.740 --> 00:17:22.240
though, is a site
where you can--

00:17:22.240 --> 00:17:26.750
it's an unlike private
property, or reservation land,

00:17:26.750 --> 00:17:30.740
or national forests.

00:17:30.740 --> 00:17:34.400
There's not really a sign of
when you enter or you exit it.

00:17:34.400 --> 00:17:37.100
The rules are not obvious.

00:17:37.100 --> 00:17:39.140
It's protected by the
Bureau of Land Management

00:17:39.140 --> 00:17:40.100
et cetera, et cetera.

00:17:40.100 --> 00:17:44.740
So you can kind of exist there.

00:17:44.740 --> 00:17:48.230
It's kind of what I like to
think of as a socialist anomaly

00:17:48.230 --> 00:17:52.011
in our capitalist society.

00:17:52.011 --> 00:17:53.510
And while it has a
lot of problems--

00:17:53.510 --> 00:17:55.718
I'm not going to get into
the real political problems

00:17:55.718 --> 00:17:57.380
of public lands--

00:17:57.380 --> 00:18:02.510
it proposed for me one of
the utopic ideas for me,

00:18:02.510 --> 00:18:06.980
which is, if we unfix
ourselves from property,

00:18:06.980 --> 00:18:10.310
what kind of society or what
kind of body emerges from that?

00:18:12.980 --> 00:18:14.630
And quickly, this
is the map of Utah.

00:18:14.630 --> 00:18:17.360
Everything that is
yellow is public lands.

00:18:17.360 --> 00:18:19.260
So 70% of Utah is public lands.

00:18:19.260 --> 00:18:21.035
So there's massive
swaths of space.

00:18:24.704 --> 00:18:26.120
Also, when you're
in public lands,

00:18:26.120 --> 00:18:27.411
it's really like feels endless.

00:18:32.300 --> 00:18:35.990
Another thing I ran into while
I was out there is Lake Powell.

00:18:35.990 --> 00:18:39.629
Lake Powell-- I think this
is kind of obvious just

00:18:39.629 --> 00:18:40.670
by looking at this image.

00:18:40.670 --> 00:18:43.110
But it's very surreal looking.

00:18:43.110 --> 00:18:45.230
And of course, I was
attracted to the surrealism

00:18:45.230 --> 00:18:47.180
of much of the
landscape there, which

00:18:47.180 --> 00:18:52.130
is why I started to stage
this science fiction there.

00:18:52.130 --> 00:18:59.810
But I, later on, discovered
that it was a damned canyon.

00:18:59.810 --> 00:19:01.850
And so the reason it
looks the way that it does

00:19:01.850 --> 00:19:04.400
is because it's essentially
like a full glass of water.

00:19:04.400 --> 00:19:06.650
There's no real
edge to this water.

00:19:06.650 --> 00:19:08.159
There's no particulation.

00:19:08.159 --> 00:19:09.950
It's just these sort
of rocks emerging out.

00:19:09.950 --> 00:19:12.140
And then when you dive
into the water, of course,

00:19:12.140 --> 00:19:14.112
it's this canyon
that's down there.

00:19:14.112 --> 00:19:16.070
And so when I discovered
this, it became like--

00:19:19.150 --> 00:19:20.340
well, it's deeply sad.

00:19:24.080 --> 00:19:25.820
You have to imagine,
then, that there's

00:19:25.820 --> 00:19:28.040
this tremendous world
under there that's

00:19:28.040 --> 00:19:32.780
been submerged by this decision
for intervention into the land.

00:19:32.780 --> 00:19:33.790
So that has actually--

00:19:33.790 --> 00:19:36.140
I'm diverging from this
project for a second here,

00:19:36.140 --> 00:19:39.920
which is, that led me to
doing a series of works

00:19:39.920 --> 00:19:43.940
that you're actually going
to see in the Radcliffe show.

00:19:43.940 --> 00:19:46.460
And these were taken
by Todd Nichols.

00:19:46.460 --> 00:19:50.547
The black and white photos were
taken by Todd Nichols in 1956.

00:19:50.547 --> 00:19:51.380
He's a photographer.

00:19:51.380 --> 00:19:54.600
He went to Glen Canyon,
which was the name of it

00:19:54.600 --> 00:19:57.500
it became Lake Powell.

00:19:57.500 --> 00:20:00.530
And that's the Colorado River
that runs through Glen Canyon.

00:20:00.530 --> 00:20:05.005
And he went and documented
and archived that landscape.

00:20:05.005 --> 00:20:07.130
And so I made these works
where I ripped images out

00:20:07.130 --> 00:20:12.410
of his catalog, and made these
sort of liquid interventions

00:20:12.410 --> 00:20:15.440
of either kind of
tracing what would

00:20:15.440 --> 00:20:19.100
seem like the new line of
water, and what has disappeared.

00:20:19.100 --> 00:20:21.140
Or sometimes, it's just
more aggressive kind

00:20:21.140 --> 00:20:24.380
of ejaculations on the page.

00:20:24.380 --> 00:20:30.280
But this sort of
notion of obscuring,

00:20:30.280 --> 00:20:32.900
or a mark of that
kind of loss of what's

00:20:32.900 --> 00:20:34.474
happened to that landscape.

00:20:37.380 --> 00:20:41.810
I'm going to play a
clip just quickly.

00:20:41.810 --> 00:20:44.094
This is going to be a
scene that moves us.

00:20:44.094 --> 00:20:45.510
Part of why I'm
playing this scene

00:20:45.510 --> 00:20:51.240
is it starts with Matana
Roberts on saxophone.

00:20:51.240 --> 00:20:54.000
It will move to
Mother Flawless, who

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.640
plays a clairvoyant psyche--

00:20:56.640 --> 00:20:58.492
and by that, I mean mind.

00:20:58.492 --> 00:21:00.908
So again, we're talking about
the metaphysical character--

00:21:03.660 --> 00:21:09.780
and who is reciting a
quote from Karen Barad's,

00:21:09.780 --> 00:21:12.670
"What is the measure of
nothingness, infinity,

00:21:12.670 --> 00:21:15.330
virtuality, and justice."

00:21:15.330 --> 00:21:16.830
And then it moves
into the desert.

00:21:16.830 --> 00:21:18.354
And another thing
to pay attention

00:21:18.354 --> 00:21:20.520
to is really unfortunate,
is that I have to show you

00:21:20.520 --> 00:21:21.697
three screens at once.

00:21:21.697 --> 00:21:23.530
But these are supposed
to be 7 foot screens.

00:21:23.530 --> 00:21:26.760
So you'll see things that--

00:21:26.760 --> 00:21:28.470
the scale is so
important to this work,

00:21:28.470 --> 00:21:31.740
being able to really
be inside the work.

00:21:31.740 --> 00:21:35.580
And you'll see that insects, and
humans, and things are scaled

00:21:35.580 --> 00:21:37.347
at the same scale and whatever.

00:21:37.347 --> 00:21:38.838
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:21:38.838 --> 00:21:41.323
[SAXOPHONE PLAYING]

00:22:27.610 --> 00:22:34.500
- Nothingness, a void,
an absence of matter,

00:22:34.500 --> 00:22:41.050
a blank page, utter silence,
no thing, no thought,

00:22:41.050 --> 00:22:47.520
no awareness, complete
insensibility.

00:22:47.520 --> 00:22:51.120
So we utter some words
about nothingness.

00:22:51.120 --> 00:22:53.010
What's there to say?

00:22:53.010 --> 00:22:55.830
Probably began
how could anything

00:22:55.830 --> 00:23:01.200
be said about nothing without
violating its very nature,

00:23:01.200 --> 00:23:06.760
perhaps, even its
conditions of possibility?

00:23:06.760 --> 00:23:09.480
And have we not
already said too much

00:23:09.480 --> 00:23:13.080
simply in pronouncing its name?

00:23:13.080 --> 00:23:19.224
Perhaps, we should let the
emptiness speak for itself.

