00:25:22.490 --> 00:25:24.210
- OK, I really
cut you off there.

00:25:24.210 --> 00:25:28.030
But we must move on.

00:25:28.030 --> 00:25:32.280
So the tiny character you
see there in the center--

00:25:32.280 --> 00:25:33.840
little orange jump suit--

00:25:36.720 --> 00:25:40.200
that's a character I
call our acting agent.

00:25:40.200 --> 00:25:41.700
That's the obsurveyer.

00:25:41.700 --> 00:25:45.660
So I was thinking
a lot about land

00:25:45.660 --> 00:25:54.240
surveying as a first stage in
kind of monetizing or dividing

00:25:54.240 --> 00:25:55.440
up land.

00:25:55.440 --> 00:26:00.900
But this character spends their
time in the desert observing.

00:26:04.450 --> 00:26:08.320
And they also kind of perform
being the camera in a way.

00:26:08.320 --> 00:26:10.100
Because they're always
holding the camera.

00:26:10.100 --> 00:26:13.240
And as you noticed, like, the
camera on the other screen

00:26:13.240 --> 00:26:14.860
is being adjusted.

00:26:14.860 --> 00:26:17.341
It's sort of more alive
than the landscape

00:26:17.341 --> 00:26:18.340
in a way at that moment.

00:26:21.700 --> 00:26:23.610
The other thing that
occurs in the desert

00:26:23.610 --> 00:26:30.240
is we follow two, what
I call, free radicals.

00:26:30.240 --> 00:26:35.430
And that is a pun on both the
electron-seeking molecule--

00:26:35.430 --> 00:26:40.110
like an unstable molecule
that's useful for modes

00:26:40.110 --> 00:26:43.260
of combustion and other
things that free radicals are

00:26:43.260 --> 00:26:45.140
good at--

00:26:45.140 --> 00:26:51.120
and also, kind of a radicalized
body, or a agent of protest,

00:26:51.120 --> 00:26:54.822
like somebody who's
embodying that.

00:26:54.822 --> 00:26:56.280
And I like this
idea that something

00:26:56.280 --> 00:26:58.640
could be both like kind
of human and molecule.

00:27:01.410 --> 00:27:10.080
So they spend a lot of their
time collecting material waste.

00:27:10.080 --> 00:27:14.910
The waste that exists in a kind
of focused way in the black box

00:27:14.910 --> 00:27:18.300
theater kind of exist
on their bodies.

00:27:18.300 --> 00:27:21.060
They are kind of always
collecting, and loading up,

00:27:21.060 --> 00:27:24.180
and unloading as they move
through the landscape.

00:27:24.180 --> 00:27:26.820
Here they're collecting
water from a leaky pipe.

00:27:26.820 --> 00:27:31.124
And water becomes also--

00:27:31.124 --> 00:27:32.790
I mentioned this
before about the water.

00:27:32.790 --> 00:27:34.706
But one of the big things
for me about the dam

00:27:34.706 --> 00:27:39.000
was [SIGHS] just thinking
about water that flows

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:41.550
and water that's controlled,
and things that flows

00:27:41.550 --> 00:27:43.204
and things that are controlled.

00:27:43.204 --> 00:27:45.120
And so then the leak
becomes really important.

00:27:45.120 --> 00:27:49.560
Because it's this place where,
even when we try and control

00:27:49.560 --> 00:27:50.730
things, things escape.

00:27:55.130 --> 00:28:01.660
And this is sort
of a dance sequence

00:28:01.660 --> 00:28:03.160
that, for me, is
like a kind of take

00:28:03.160 --> 00:28:05.750
on flagging, which is
part of queer culture--

00:28:05.750 --> 00:28:12.460
is historically used to identify
that someone, one, was queer,

00:28:12.460 --> 00:28:16.095
and two, what they
might want from you,

00:28:16.095 --> 00:28:17.470
or what you might
want from them.

00:28:21.810 --> 00:28:24.970
So I brought two dancers
with me, Niv Acosta, and Jen

00:28:24.970 --> 00:28:27.260
Rosenblit, to the desert.

00:28:27.260 --> 00:28:32.280
And you might
actually be flagging

00:28:32.280 --> 00:28:35.070
like the sun, and the
water, and the atmosphere--

00:28:35.070 --> 00:28:39.460
like, that the
fighting might occur

00:28:39.460 --> 00:28:44.510
not as a human interaction,
but as a kind of way

00:28:44.510 --> 00:28:50.090
of visibility or engagement
with an environment.

00:28:50.090 --> 00:28:52.850
There's also a sequence
in which they measure.

00:28:52.850 --> 00:28:55.410
It's kind of a dance
sequence also--

00:28:55.410 --> 00:28:56.737
a little more abstract--

00:28:56.737 --> 00:28:58.820
where they're kind of
moving through the landscape

00:28:58.820 --> 00:29:01.310
and measuring the
space with their body.

00:29:04.160 --> 00:29:08.480
And then, in the theater,
what's happening in the theater,

00:29:08.480 --> 00:29:11.480
most often, is these
series of recitations

00:29:11.480 --> 00:29:14.831
of this text that kind of
hold the work together.

00:29:14.831 --> 00:29:16.865
So I'm going to play
one more for you.

00:29:16.865 --> 00:29:18.350
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:29:18.350 --> 00:29:21.320
[FOOTSTEPS]

00:29:30.725 --> 00:29:33.200
[EXHALES]

00:29:35.675 --> 00:29:38.150
[HEARTBEATS]

00:29:44.585 --> 00:29:48.050
- There was a wall.

00:29:48.050 --> 00:29:49.726
It did not look important.

00:29:57.380 --> 00:30:00.820
It was built of uncut
stone, roughly mortared.

00:30:12.228 --> 00:30:14.708
[OBJECT FALLING ON THE GROUND]

00:30:18.210 --> 00:30:20.706
We're across the roadway.

00:30:20.706 --> 00:30:26.210
Instead of having a
gate, it degenerated

00:30:26.210 --> 00:30:34.317
into a mere geometry, a line.

00:30:37.627 --> 00:30:38.710
And I did have a boundary.

00:30:46.880 --> 00:30:49.840
But the idea was important.

00:30:49.840 --> 00:30:50.380
It was real.

00:30:56.870 --> 00:31:16.000
Like all walls, it was
ambiguous, two-faced

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:20.860
What was inside and what
was outside depended

00:31:20.860 --> 00:31:22.220
which side of it you were on.

00:31:45.220 --> 00:31:47.720
[SMACKS LIPS]

