And then anyone
who is reciting--

00:32:38.105 --> 00:32:39.730
any time there's a
recitation going on,

00:32:39.730 --> 00:32:43.960
it's kind of really focused
on a single activity,

00:32:43.960 --> 00:32:46.780
or gesture, and the language.

00:32:46.780 --> 00:32:53.320
And so I'm interested in
the way this kind of working

00:32:53.320 --> 00:32:56.440
with a certain material
and the language

00:32:56.440 --> 00:32:58.260
sort of make its own meaning.

00:32:58.260 --> 00:33:01.772
So that lipstick starts to
have a lot more layers to it

00:33:01.772 --> 00:33:03.730
when we're talking about
boundaries, and lines,

00:33:03.730 --> 00:33:04.930
and things, right?

00:33:04.930 --> 00:33:09.400
This is another scene where the
action is pushing all the air

00:33:09.400 --> 00:33:11.290
out of an air mattress.

00:33:11.290 --> 00:33:13.540
There's a lot of camping
gear throughout this work.

00:33:13.540 --> 00:33:14.500
You can imagine why.

00:33:14.500 --> 00:33:15.990
We started out in the desert.

00:33:15.990 --> 00:33:18.880
It continues on throughout.

00:33:18.880 --> 00:33:21.790
And also thinking a
lot about nomadic--

00:33:21.790 --> 00:33:23.890
like, the material
of our contemporary,

00:33:23.890 --> 00:33:26.290
like the commerce
around nomad-ism

00:33:26.290 --> 00:33:30.010
in contemporary culture.

00:33:30.010 --> 00:33:32.620
And this is another scene.

00:33:32.620 --> 00:33:37.260
Jen Rosenblit does this
