00:33:45.270 --> 00:33:48.670
she becomes completely
ensconced in the mud,

00:33:48.670 --> 00:33:51.999
and actually, sort of
becomes the landscape.

00:33:51.999 --> 00:33:53.790
And this becomes an
important thing for me,

00:33:53.790 --> 00:33:56.700
is looking for ways in which
the work in the theater

00:33:56.700 --> 00:33:58.200
can move us back
into the desert.

00:33:58.200 --> 00:34:00.250
Because at one point when
I was working on this work,

00:34:00.250 --> 00:34:01.500
I was really like, oh, my god.

00:34:01.500 --> 00:34:05.680
I have like this stark black
and the brightness of--

00:34:05.680 --> 00:34:08.100
everything felt really
binary all of the sudden

00:34:08.100 --> 00:34:09.840
between these two worlds.

00:34:09.840 --> 00:34:14.010
And so I started to develop some
of this visual material that

00:34:14.010 --> 00:34:17.190
helped move me between
these two worlds.

00:34:17.190 --> 00:34:20.040
This is the shapeshifter.

00:34:20.040 --> 00:34:23.290
So this is her in her natural
state of perpetual becoming.

00:34:23.290 --> 00:34:26.880
So she's getting ready always.

00:34:26.880 --> 00:34:32.460
Played by [? Marcelo ?]
[? Gutierrez. ?] And one of her

00:34:32.460 --> 00:34:36.473
tasks is taking care of
this Chelsea Manning jacket,

00:34:36.473 --> 00:34:38.639
which she does kind of in
a loving and fetish-y kind

00:34:38.639 --> 00:34:40.889
of way, like stroking
and caring for it.

00:34:40.889 --> 00:34:44.520
And Chelsea Manning's jacket
shows up in the second piece

00:34:44.520 --> 00:34:45.760
as well.

00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:48.780
But what I'm kind of
interested in with Chelsea--

00:34:48.780 --> 00:34:52.290
and this is kind of
this way that the now

00:34:52.290 --> 00:34:53.880
shows up in this work.

00:34:53.880 --> 00:34:55.620
So there's always
a kind of layer

00:34:55.620 --> 00:34:58.740
of real political event
merging with this kind

00:34:58.740 --> 00:35:02.550
of strange fantastical space.

00:35:02.550 --> 00:35:05.490
But Manning, for me, is
another kind of leak, right?

00:35:05.490 --> 00:35:13.890
So it's not only the information
leaks, but also a leaky body,

00:35:13.890 --> 00:35:20.140
a body that's not fitting, or
is transitioning, et cetera.

00:35:25.020 --> 00:35:30.180
So the shapeshifter, when
she's not in her natural state,

00:35:30.180 --> 00:35:32.040
becomes other things.

00:35:32.040 --> 00:35:37.050
In this case, this is kind of
a remake of a famous painting,

00:35:37.050 --> 00:35:39.530
for anyone who's not
familiar with art history--

00:35:39.530 --> 00:35:42.180
very canonical work.

00:35:42.180 --> 00:35:44.190
Well, there we go.

00:35:44.190 --> 00:35:47.460
Olympia-- if you haven't
seen it, there it is.

00:35:47.460 --> 00:35:50.040
Back to this version
on air mattresses.

00:35:52.710 --> 00:35:58.440
In this scene, there's a
recitation from [INAUDIBLE]--

00:35:58.440 --> 00:36:00.540
I don't know if I'm
ever saying that right--

00:36:00.540 --> 00:36:02.380
"Screwball Asses."

00:36:02.380 --> 00:36:06.420
So it's kind of taking this
vision of the prostitute

00:36:06.420 --> 00:36:09.420
through Marcelo's body.

00:36:09.420 --> 00:36:14.440
And the text kind of speaks
of the virtues of womanhood

00:36:14.440 --> 00:36:18.054
through a vision of
the lesbian body.

00:36:18.054 --> 00:36:19.720
Anyway, you can imagine
where that goes.

00:36:19.720 --> 00:36:23.170
OK, so the other.

00:36:23.170 --> 00:36:26.490
Character is Aunt Be/e.

00:36:26.490 --> 00:36:28.000
This is Aunt Be/e.

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:30.190
This is a shapeshifter
as Aunt Be/e.

00:36:30.190 --> 00:36:38.752
So Aunt Be/e, that's B-E
slash E, as in being, or a--

00:36:38.752 --> 00:36:40.138
OK, you get it.

00:36:42.850 --> 00:36:48.010
And that's because this
character is also--

00:36:48.010 --> 00:36:53.010
so Aunt Be/e is performing
as reproductive labor.

00:36:56.630 --> 00:36:58.130
And this is what
a little insight

00:36:58.130 --> 00:37:02.000
in how I develop the character,
is I was thinking about bees.

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:05.740
Because that's a really
obvious idea about labor.

00:37:05.740 --> 00:37:08.210
And I found this
fantastic photo of a bee.

00:37:08.210 --> 00:37:15.830
And that got me to creating the
yellow dust on [? Neyland ?]

00:37:15.830 --> 00:37:17.637
for this scene.

00:37:17.637 --> 00:37:19.220
Now I'm not interested
in, when people

00:37:19.220 --> 00:37:22.850
watch my work, that they,
like, get all of that.

00:37:22.850 --> 00:37:26.390
I'm interested in you
having an experience,

00:37:26.390 --> 00:37:28.100
and that there's
something kind of--

00:37:31.505 --> 00:37:35.420
I'm into manipulating
people, actually.

00:37:35.420 --> 00:37:37.550
I want to seduce you with
a certain amount of image

00:37:37.550 --> 00:37:39.589
and sound, so that
you kind of believe me

00:37:39.589 --> 00:37:40.880
whatever I put in front of you.

00:37:40.880 --> 00:37:45.450
And so you could unpack this
work with that level of detail.

00:37:45.450 --> 00:37:47.780
But I'm sort of more
interested in that you just

00:37:47.780 --> 00:37:50.044
become kind of absorbed
in the sort of world

00:37:50.044 --> 00:37:50.960
that I create for you.

00:37:53.530 --> 00:37:56.480
And anyway, so
reproductive labor

00:37:56.480 --> 00:37:59.750
is set with the
task of operating

00:37:59.750 --> 00:38:03.130
a Xerox machine and a juicer.

00:38:03.130 --> 00:38:11.890
The juicer I'm
interested in, because it

00:38:11.890 --> 00:38:16.600
changes a solid to a liquid.

00:38:16.600 --> 00:38:18.640
It also has kind of
a component of waste

00:38:18.640 --> 00:38:21.220
that happens that's really
beautiful, and then also

00:38:21.220 --> 00:38:23.080
for the aesthetic reasons.

00:38:23.080 --> 00:38:26.192
So this also allowed me to
create the scene in which we

00:38:26.192 --> 00:38:28.150
get something that's very
similar to the strata

00:38:28.150 --> 00:38:30.050
in the desert.

00:38:30.050 --> 00:38:33.369
And it also became like
a way to segue into--

00:38:33.369 --> 00:38:34.910
and I was also
interested in this one

00:38:34.910 --> 00:38:39.050
with the sort of overflow
excess that occurs.

00:38:39.050 --> 00:38:44.810
So the exhibition "Shabby But
Thriving" at the New Museum

00:38:44.810 --> 00:38:47.960
is the second in the series.

00:38:47.960 --> 00:38:50.690
It's the video that's
based around the body.

00:38:53.826 --> 00:38:55.700
A lot of the way this
work is being developed

00:38:55.700 --> 00:38:58.220
is sort of with the resources
I can glean to make it.

00:38:58.220 --> 00:39:01.527
So through the
residency at the museum,

00:39:01.527 --> 00:39:03.110
they offer you to
work in the building

00:39:03.110 --> 00:39:05.510
next door to the New Museum,
which is this old Bowery

00:39:05.510 --> 00:39:07.580
building that's dilapidated.

00:39:07.580 --> 00:39:11.517
And they're actually going
to be rent renovating it

00:39:11.517 --> 00:39:12.350
into the New Museum.

00:39:12.350 --> 00:39:14.330
But that's a future story.

00:39:14.330 --> 00:39:17.160
So what I started to
think, I was, like, OK,

00:39:17.160 --> 00:39:20.420
how am I going from the
desert to the theater?

00:39:20.420 --> 00:39:22.190
Does it make sense
to be in a building?

00:39:22.190 --> 00:39:24.929
Does that even make
sense to be in a city?

00:39:24.929 --> 00:39:26.720
So then I got really
interested in the idea

00:39:26.720 --> 00:39:28.920
that the building
was its own body,

00:39:28.920 --> 00:39:31.670
and that we could do this whole
piece sort of hermetically

00:39:31.670 --> 00:39:33.607
sealed in this building.

00:39:33.607 --> 00:39:34.940
We would never leave this space.

00:39:34.940 --> 00:39:37.640
And it would be this
sort of internal world,

00:39:37.640 --> 00:39:41.490
and bodies within
antibodies that would occur.

00:39:41.490 --> 00:39:44.630
So the insulation
is set up with what

00:39:44.630 --> 00:39:46.220
is a kind of quasi-living room.

00:39:46.220 --> 00:39:50.650
There's a carpet that's
pretty filthy at this point,

00:39:50.650 --> 00:39:52.150
because it's a light
colored carpet.

00:39:52.150 --> 00:39:56.330
So it attracts everyone
who walks through it.

00:39:56.330 --> 00:40:02.210
There's this couch, which
is kind of excerpted.

00:40:02.210 --> 00:40:03.410
I'll go to this scene.

00:40:03.410 --> 00:40:06.110
So there's a scene--

00:40:06.110 --> 00:40:11.250
there's three children that
occupy couches with underglow.

00:40:11.250 --> 00:40:13.780
They're kind of
like planets, right?

00:40:17.820 --> 00:40:22.720
And so this object in the
room is a gutted couch.

00:40:22.720 --> 00:40:25.030
There's a scene in which
the couches become gutted,

00:40:25.030 --> 00:40:26.440
ultimately.

00:40:26.440 --> 00:40:32.930
And then it's propped up on
these cast dirt bags of soil.

00:40:32.930 --> 00:40:36.952
And that's developed from
one of the scenes which

00:40:36.952 --> 00:40:38.035
you can kind of see here--

00:40:40.960 --> 00:40:43.450
this couch on the
left, actually--

00:40:43.450 --> 00:40:48.220
which was built around the idea
that each one of the children

00:40:48.220 --> 00:40:53.560
is a different celestial
body, AKA a dwarf planet.

00:40:53.560 --> 00:40:55.630
So that's Pluto.

00:40:55.630 --> 00:40:57.790
And the dirt bags
are kind of, for me,

00:40:57.790 --> 00:41:03.270
reminiscent of the narrative
behind the name of Pluto,

00:41:03.270 --> 00:41:05.310
which is, one, the
god of the underworld.

00:41:05.310 --> 00:41:07.080
But more importantly,
it can be also seen

00:41:07.080 --> 00:41:14.440
as like a mineral, resources,
and the keeper of the earth,

00:41:14.440 --> 00:41:16.580
and soil, and stuff like that.

00:41:16.580 --> 00:41:19.360
Anyway, so the
seats of the couch

00:41:19.360 --> 00:41:22.070
have been replaced with
these bags of dirt.

00:41:22.070 --> 00:41:25.810
And so that's where
this sculpture

00:41:25.810 --> 00:41:32.810
object skeleton thing developed
from that's in the room.

00:41:32.810 --> 00:41:36.680
And also, what you see
here is you've got--

00:41:36.680 --> 00:41:38.240
I'm going to go to
this one again--

00:41:38.240 --> 00:41:40.210
a false wall that
was built. So you've

00:41:40.210 --> 00:41:43.290
got it sort of raw,
drywall, false wall.

00:41:43.290 --> 00:41:46.100
I was interested in the sort
of exposed architecture.

00:41:46.100 --> 00:41:48.290
And then what the
second screen is

00:41:48.290 --> 00:41:49.790
a actually a piece
of drywall that's

00:41:49.790 --> 00:41:52.244
been leaned against the wall.

00:41:52.244 --> 00:41:53.660
So you have these
kind of elements

00:41:53.660 --> 00:41:56.840
of a building being built
within this environment

00:41:56.840 --> 00:41:58.130
of the installation.

00:41:58.130 --> 00:42:02.780
All right, so there are these
children, which I have already

00:42:02.780 --> 00:42:05.780
explained are--

00:42:05.780 --> 00:42:10.520
they occupy what is
the living room space.

00:42:10.520 --> 00:42:12.440
And the living room is
also called the psyche.

00:42:12.440 --> 00:42:14.360
These are things that are
also noted in the credits,

00:42:14.360 --> 00:42:15.734
like they were in
the last piece.

00:42:19.220 --> 00:42:22.550
And I got interested in
the idea of dwarf planets,

00:42:22.550 --> 00:42:24.860
not only because the
children are small--

00:42:24.860 --> 00:42:26.990
I like really easy connections.

00:42:26.990 --> 00:42:29.341
I'm really interested
in easy connections.

00:42:33.030 --> 00:42:39.510
But there's something about the
dwarf planet, especially Pluto,

00:42:39.510 --> 00:42:43.470
which you know was kicked
out of the solar system.

00:42:43.470 --> 00:42:46.940
I'm interested in this idea
of what's an acceptable--

00:42:46.940 --> 00:42:47.940
when are you a planet?

00:42:47.940 --> 00:42:48.981
When are you on a planet?

00:42:51.790 --> 00:42:53.440
It's the kind of
othering situation

00:42:53.440 --> 00:42:56.090
I think is fascinating.

00:42:56.090 --> 00:42:58.600
And then the children
all have jumpsuits

00:42:58.600 --> 00:43:01.270
that match their couches.

00:43:01.270 --> 00:43:08.730
And so the couches are, of
course, bodies unto themselves.

00:43:08.730 --> 00:43:10.210
They're hosts for bodies.

00:43:10.210 --> 00:43:13.010
That's how we hang out
with them, in general.

00:43:13.010 --> 00:43:15.110
But I think, in this
case, the children

00:43:15.110 --> 00:43:18.755
kind of operate in a quasi-space
of they are of the couch.

00:43:22.729 --> 00:43:24.770
And I was also interest
in working with children,

00:43:24.770 --> 00:43:33.430
because I was interested in sort
of a state of pre-definition.

00:43:33.430 --> 00:43:36.550
Kids also sit somewhere
between reality and fantasy

00:43:36.550 --> 00:43:38.260
very easily.

00:43:38.260 --> 00:43:40.231
And so what they perform--

00:43:40.231 --> 00:43:41.980
at one point, this
child who's taking care

00:43:41.980 --> 00:43:46.030
of a fish tank and a fish--

00:43:46.030 --> 00:43:50.410
which also, for me, symbolizes
the desert in this work.

00:43:50.410 --> 00:43:52.840
You can see the tank is kind
of like half full of water.

00:43:52.840 --> 00:43:54.790
And there's this big red rock.

00:43:54.790 --> 00:43:58.164
And there's a lot of
focus on this tank.

00:43:58.164 --> 00:43:59.830
So I like that the
desert could show up,

00:43:59.830 --> 00:44:03.812
but it would be in the
kind of innermost space

00:44:03.812 --> 00:44:04.520
within this work.

00:44:08.700 --> 00:44:14.370
This child ends up performing,
caring for the fish,

00:44:14.370 --> 00:44:16.860
but also becoming the fish,
and plays a fish out of water,

00:44:16.860 --> 00:44:21.990
kind of called convulsing
at some point on the floor.

00:44:21.990 --> 00:44:27.882
This one, [? Erris, ?] is set
with the task of fly swatting.

00:44:27.882 --> 00:44:29.340
I was thinking a
lot about violence

00:44:29.340 --> 00:44:31.530
throughout the whole
making of this piece.

00:44:31.530 --> 00:44:35.580
And I'm really interested
in micro-violence,

00:44:35.580 --> 00:44:38.880
or the small things, the things
that we overlook as violence,

00:44:38.880 --> 00:44:40.530
like killing a fly.

00:44:40.530 --> 00:44:42.930
Most of us don't think
twice about that.

00:44:42.930 --> 00:44:48.930
So I'm interested in kind of
amplifying small things often.

00:44:48.930 --> 00:44:52.440
In this case, the room starts
sort of speaking to the child.

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:58.110
And it's not clear if the child
is chasing a fly or the room

00:44:58.110 --> 00:44:59.600
itself also.

00:45:02.550 --> 00:45:05.400
And then this one, Pluto.

00:45:05.400 --> 00:45:11.460
Pluto ends up performing
like a bird of prey,

00:45:11.460 --> 00:45:13.290
and does its beautiful
scene of like kind

00:45:13.290 --> 00:45:15.780
of squawking as a
bird in relation

00:45:15.780 --> 00:45:19.590
to this fish in the tank.

00:45:19.590 --> 00:45:27.130
And that's another scene just
showing the bags of soil.

00:45:27.130 --> 00:45:29.860
So the Manning jacket
shows up again here,

00:45:29.860 --> 00:45:36.370
and is worn by Keyon Gaskin,
another dancer performer--

00:45:36.370 --> 00:45:40.420
and again, to bring the
weight of the leaky body

00:45:40.420 --> 00:45:46.255
into this scene, which
takes place in a stairwell.

00:45:46.255 --> 00:45:47.630
So another one of
the scenes that

00:45:47.630 --> 00:45:51.020
moves throughout the whole
work is we move from the top

00:45:51.020 --> 00:45:53.900
to the bottom of the building
through this stairwell

00:45:53.900 --> 00:45:56.090
throughout the whole work.

00:45:56.090 --> 00:45:57.500
And in that process,
there's kind

00:45:57.500 --> 00:46:02.810
of just this movement of
the destructed couches,

00:46:02.810 --> 00:46:05.250
and all this sort of-- so
the garbage, again, shows up.

00:46:05.250 --> 00:46:07.970
Waste shows up again
as a kind of movement

00:46:07.970 --> 00:46:09.620
from and through the building.

00:46:09.620 --> 00:46:12.560
And it's also very
much like a descent.

00:46:12.560 --> 00:46:18.860
The whole thing is moving
downwards in the building.

00:46:18.860 --> 00:46:21.140
So I think of that as kind
of a movement of mouth

00:46:21.140 --> 00:46:24.920
to anus, or like a process of
moving through the entire body.

00:46:27.380 --> 00:46:28.880
Because it's a
two-screen piece, you

00:46:28.880 --> 00:46:31.700
see this descent
happening simultaneously.

00:46:34.220 --> 00:46:37.340
Ms. Manning is one
of the characters.

00:46:37.340 --> 00:46:39.680
And the pregnant
backpacker is the other.

00:46:39.680 --> 00:46:42.346
So this, for me,
was this feeling.

00:46:42.346 --> 00:46:44.720
When I was thinking about all
of this like weight bearing

00:46:44.720 --> 00:46:53.540
and bodies that hold
symbolically and in reality

00:46:53.540 --> 00:46:59.510
social and political
weight, I thought of--

00:46:59.510 --> 00:47:01.159
with the pregnant
body, that's already

00:47:01.159 --> 00:47:02.450
like a physical kind of weight.

00:47:02.450 --> 00:47:05.030
And then I was like, OK, we'll
throw a backpack on that,

00:47:05.030 --> 00:47:06.860
and make it just
like this kind of

00:47:06.860 --> 00:47:10.086
counter weighted
impossibility on top

00:47:10.086 --> 00:47:11.960
of the weight of everything
else that's going

00:47:11.960 --> 00:47:16.280
to be taken down the stairwell.

00:47:16.280 --> 00:47:19.049
And that's entering
the basement,

00:47:19.049 --> 00:47:20.340
which we'll get to in a minute.

00:47:20.340 --> 00:47:26.760
But then there's
another scene, which

00:47:26.760 --> 00:47:28.710
I'm just going to do
this, so you can actually

00:47:28.710 --> 00:47:37.630
see both characters,
Keyon and [? Steiner. ?]

00:47:37.630 --> 00:47:40.190
This is the bathroom,
or the kidneys.

00:47:40.190 --> 00:47:43.360
This is the detox tub talks.

00:47:43.360 --> 00:47:49.870
And they spend their time
in the bathroom discussing--

00:47:49.870 --> 00:47:52.930
mostly, they're discussing
language, and words,

00:47:52.930 --> 00:47:59.976
and whether or how words are
functional or non functional.

00:47:59.976 --> 00:48:01.600
And then that leads
into a conversation

00:48:01.600 --> 00:48:08.470
about needing to name a
new party, a lesbian party.

00:48:08.470 --> 00:48:10.720
Turns out it's a
lesbian dance party.

00:48:10.720 --> 00:48:12.640
It could be any party, though.

00:48:12.640 --> 00:48:16.210
And in the end, the
result is that they

00:48:16.210 --> 00:48:18.085
get to calling the party lies.

00:48:20.780 --> 00:48:25.150
But this is maybe the
most humorous section.

00:48:29.170 --> 00:48:30.540
Everything's a little dark.

00:48:30.540 --> 00:48:34.374
But this is, maybe, the lighter
part of the work in that way.

00:48:34.374 --> 00:48:35.790
The other thing I
want to say here

00:48:35.790 --> 00:48:42.750
is that this scene is a
remake of Death of Marat.

00:48:42.750 --> 00:48:47.880
Again, I'm interested in
co-opting the canon here.

00:48:47.880 --> 00:48:52.050
And what I was interested
in the story of Murat

00:48:52.050 --> 00:48:57.901
is that he was working as--

00:48:57.901 --> 00:49:00.150
most of you probably already
know the story of Murat--

00:49:00.150 --> 00:49:03.180
but was part of the
French Revolution,

00:49:03.180 --> 00:49:07.170
and was a writer, activist,
as you would call it,

00:49:07.170 --> 00:49:09.060
and was killed.

00:49:09.060 --> 00:49:10.980
The scene that you see
there in the painting

00:49:10.980 --> 00:49:16.170
was killed by a woman
from the Bourgeois class.

00:49:16.170 --> 00:49:20.132
So I didn't want
anyone to kill anyone.

00:49:20.132 --> 00:49:21.840
Or I was interested
in the way that death

00:49:21.840 --> 00:49:25.530
